ball.post_text: 3.40 pm England have got through a whole session without losing a wicket, and with the sun bathing the ground at Trent Bridge, they'd fancy doing it again. Not least because Jos Buttler and Ben Stokes have been very very clear with their plans. They've concentrated on defence. They've played with soft hands. And now, facing their biggest threat - reverse swing - they're playing with straight bats and low backlifts. This is a contest, even if India are 348 runs ahead. So don't you leave that seat. We'll be back in about 20 minutes
ball.text: full on off stump, Buttler works it through to the right of mid-on. That's tea, and it's a bit disappointing because the action was properly hotting up
this reverses away and Buttler, standing quite still in his crease, sends it away through the covers.

sensational! The perfect inswinging yorker. And geez, it moves so much! The ball starts well outside off and then changing direction to hunt down Buttler's stumps. Good job by the batsman to keep it out, again by playing straight
he can ignore this one too seeing as its a good distance outside off. Shami's cranking it up though - hits 90 mph - which is quite useful when the ball is reversing
shortish and outside off, lets it go

ball.pre_text: Jims: "Is Johnny coming to bat ?" --- The broadcast showed him padded up, so probably
ball.text: full on off stump, Buttler drives to mid-off. Commendable cricket from these two. They've sized up the ball is reversing. They know their stumps are in danger. And so they are playing as straight as they can

ball.post_text: WATCH - India lose review against Buttler (India only)
ball.text: good length on middle and off, Stokes defends gently
lunging outside the off stump to drive a well flighted delivery outside off to the left of mid-off

leans into another pretty-looking drive. Buttler's footwork to spin is impressive. He's getting inside the line to open up the off side and he's only going for the drive against the turn after getting ot the pitch of the ball
tosses it up on off stump, Buttler gets inside the line to drive to mid-off
a little too much flight there and Buttler crashes it through extra cover having got to the ball on the full.
full and on off stump, defends

ball.post_text: Right then. We're having fun again. Bless reverse swing and thats why there are three slips now
ball.text: holds its line this time outside off and Stokes, worried by the reverse, reaches out away from his body to defend it. Lucky not to nick off

goes wide of the crease to get the ball to swing into Stokes, who does well to put a straight bat in front of pad. Lbws become a prime way to dismiss batsmen when the ball is reversing and both Stokes and Buttler are trying to prevent that
back of a length and outside off, Stokes leaves
full and a shade outside off, Stokes defends with as soft hands as possible

ball.post_text: Goes around the wicket to Stokes. Two slips in
ball.pre_text: MH: "Hey Al (And Naga), how's it going there on the field? Intense? Eng relaxed? India dropping shoulders? Give us some insights that we can't see. " Imagine having a staring contest and concentrating on nothing other than outlasting the other guy. (In other words, a whole lot of trying not to do anything silly - which come to think of it is a perfect description of a staring contest - but waiting for the other guy to do exactly that)
ball.text: massive swing into the right-hander. Shami is definitely having some fun out there, pitching the ball right up there, close to even a yorker length. Buttler works with the movement and flicks to long leg
pushes it through on middle and leg, Stokes is quite happy to shift his weight back and flick it to short leg
big turn as the quicker delivery hitting the footmarks outside the left-hander's off stump and darts away past Stokes' defensive prod
loops it up outside off, daring Stokes to hit out through the off side. He does, sending a drive to cover
angles it into middle and leg, and Stokes opens himself up as he looks to defend, playing for the turn and being beaten on the inside edge
he is very reluctant to come forward the moment the ball is flat in trajectory. Ashwin still manages to send those deliveries right up to the batsman
good length on off stump, Buttler blocks
more reverse, and this time he lines it up on off stump too, making the inswing all the more threatening. Buttler, as he needs to, plays with a straight bat to mid-on
fuller delivery outside off, stabs it to cover

huge appeal, but umpire Erasmus shakes his head. Kohli and Shami have a quick chat and India go for the review again. Splendid bowling though. Shami is getting reverse, the pitched-up ball swerving into the right-hander, and late, leaving Buttler in a very awkward, closed-off position as he tries to flick. Ironically, the movement that puts the batsman in trouble takes the ball down leg. Ball-tracking says it would miss leg stump. India lose the review

ball.pre_text: Two slips and two men and a catching midwicket
ball.text: goes searching for the drive, and realises that would leave him playing away from the body. Stokes checks the shot and also manages to pick the gap between cover and mid-off. Brings up the 100 partnership

ball.pre_text:
Here's Shami, with two slips

Karthik: "Wish someone in the Indian lineup had shown this kind of a fight at Lords. But then again, one possible reason why India did so much better at TB was the flak they got after that test. England missing a trick here I would think by not collapsing and letting Vaughan go ballistic on twitter"
ball.text: gets the ball to curl in the air and off the pitch as well, forcing Buttler to shift himself to the leg side a bit and flick behind square leg
